        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3595747568" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1729698849006482718">I discovered the work of Charles Dickens quite late, in adulthood, and it took me several years to let myself completely caught in the net of its charms. Today, having read a large number of his novels, I consider him a brilliant storyteller with a singular verb, and I am determined to read his fictional work in its entirety.<br/>&quot;Dombey and Son&quot; is not Charles Dickens&apos;s best-known novel, far from it. However, its thousand pages contain a lovely family and social fiction that his contemporary Victor </span>
  <span id="freeText1729698849006482718" style="display:none">I discovered the work of Charles Dickens quite late, in adulthood, and it took me several years to let myself completely caught in the net of its charms. Today, having read a large number of his novels, I consider him a brilliant storyteller with a singular verb, and I am determined to read his fictional work in its entirety.<br />"Dombey and Son" is not Charles Dickens's best-known novel, far from it. However, its thousand pages contain a lovely family and social fiction that his contemporary Victor Hugo will doubtless not have disdained. All the ingredients make a Dickensian novel an extraordinary universe entirely of shattered destinies and colourful figures.<br />A novel of vanity and ambition, "Dombey &amp; Son" denounces the greed of the heart, the pretension of class, the manipulation of beings and the harshness of a society that does not spare the needy. With unique humour, Charles Dickens deploys this talent which belongs only to him, to give life to a massive gallery of characters to eat in both senses of the word.<br />I don't know of any other author of the period capable of featuring many leading and supporting characters and nimbly interlocking them with each other and giving them each a personality of its own, by turns endearing or repulsive. Likewise, each actor in this beautiful drama worked, searched and in-depth until offering the reader the best of his qualities or faults. The result is such a closeness to the ordinary heroes and heroines of the novel that we, the readers, feel ourselves becoming one of them.<br />Charles Dickens did not in any way usurp his status as a beloved author of the English Language, and I am one of his great admirers.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1729698849006482718" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


