<div id="review_3834041555" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3834041555" />
    <a title="Cozy_Pug" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/99939420-cozy-pug"><img alt="Cozy_Pug" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1643894438p2/99939420.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3834041555?book_show_action=true">May 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cozy_Pug" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cozy_Pug" href="/user/show/99939420-cozy-pug">Cozy_Pug</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/17930482-dombey-and-son">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3834041555" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12078608511733208848">This may just be the best novel I&apos;ve ever read. And until earlier this year, I&apos;d never heard of it. I&apos;ve not read all of Dickens&apos; novels, but I knew all the titles. Or thought I did. What an amazing book to stumble across, in the Dickensians! group, just in time to participate in the group read.<br/><br/>There are many characters and many themes in <u>Dombey and Son</u>. In thinking about what I want to say in my review, I keep coming back to one character and one theme. Mr Paul Dombey is that character, redempt</span>
  <span id="freeText12078608511733208848" style="display:none">This may just be the best novel I've ever read. And until earlier this year, I'd never heard of it. I've not read all of Dickens' novels, but I knew all the titles. Or thought I did. What an amazing book to stumble across, in the Dickensians! group, just in time to participate in the group read.<br /><br />There are many characters and many themes in <u>Dombey and Son</u>. In thinking about what I want to say in my review, I keep coming back to one character and one theme. Mr Paul Dombey is that character, redemption is that theme.<br /><br />Mr Dombey is a remarkable fictional creation. I think it's fair to say most people know of someone who is arrogant, focused on their career to the point of neglecting family, and hurtful in their self-absorption. That's nothing new, unfortunately. What is different is how Dickens expands these character flaws in Mr Dombey to a hyperbolic level. Mr Dombey's arrogance and fixed ideas of what is important are stunning in their rigidity and depth.<br /><br />My initial reaction to Mr Dombey - what a repugnant, cold fish of a man. But rather quickly, an odd thing happened. I began to feel sorry for him, I began to hope for something that would change him - something to open his eyes to the true treasures in his life (<b>not</b> the Firm). I wanted to see Mr Dombey experience redemption - a redemptive love, a redemptive experience - something, <i>anything</i>, to save this man from himself. <br /><br />Over the course of the novel, Dickens whips up plenty of circumstances that could move Mr Dombey in either direction on the line of redemption. It's a roller coaster ride for the reader - will Dombey reach a crisis point and see the error of his ways or will he dig in his heels and retreat further into cold, black, selfish darkness?<br /><br />Dickens plots this beautifully - at no point did I want to give up on the story. It was relentlessly compelling - I cared about Mr Dombey and all the other characters in his orbit, I needed to know how their stories would end. My edition was almost 1000 pages long, but it never felt like a massive tome. Dickens' writing and crafting of this tale is perfectly rendered - it never lags, never drags - but always pulls the reader forward, much like the new railways were pulling Britain forward at the time the novel was written.<br /><br />At its simplest level, <u>Dombey and Son</u> is a story about life, the human experience. Birth, death - love, hate - joy, sorrow - devotion, repulsion - honesty, lies - good, evil. Dickens possessed, I think, the personal experience and a high emotional intelligence that enabled him to create a story that is powerful, moving, and lasting. It's certainly a novel I will never forget - it is very much embedded in my mind and soul - the beauty of the language and syntax, the evocation of vivid emotions, the characters who are as real to me as my own family. <u>Dombey and Son</u> is a literary treasure that I will cherish and read again and again and again.<br /><br />Some of my favorite passages -<br /><br /><i>"...I hope for better things, I will pray for them, and believe that they will arrive."<br /><br />...away, with a shriek, and a roar, and a rattle, and no trace to leave behind but dust and vapour: like as in the track of the remorseless monster, Death!<br /><br />Standing together, arm in arm, they had the appearance of being more divided than if seas had rolled between them.<br /><br />In this round world of many circles within circles, do we make a weary journey from the high grade to the low, to find at last that they lie close together, that the two extremes touch, and that our journey’s end is but our starting-place?<br /><br />Awake, doomed man, while she is near! The time is flitting by; the hour is coming with an angry tread; its foot is in the house. Awake!<br /><br />The roar soon grew more loud, the passengers more numerous, the shops more busy, until she was carried onward in a stream of life setting that way, and flowing, indifferently, past marts and mansions, prisons, churches, market-places, wealth, poverty, good, and evil, like the broad river side by side with it, awakened from its dreams of rushes, willows, and green moss, and rolling on, turbid and troubled, among the works and cares of men, to the deep sea.<br /><br />To watch the shadows of the clouds and leaves, and seem to feel a sympathy with shadows. It was natural that he should. To him, life and the world were nothing else.</i><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12078608511733208848" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


