<div id="review_4088440211" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4088440211" />
    <a title="Jessica" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/202724-jessica"><img alt="Jessica" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1601676054p2/202724.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4088440211?book_show_action=true">Aug 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jessica" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jessica" href="/user/show/202724-jessica">Jessica</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/17930482-dombey-and-son">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/202724-jessica?shelf=audiobooks">audiobooks</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/202724-jessica?shelf=theclassics">theclassics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/202724-jessica?shelf=own">own</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4088440211" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13085198082561420740">This was a huge saga, and I&apos;m kind of shocked that it isn&apos;t more widely regarded/read. I first heard about it from Little Women, when Jo is packing up Laurie for school and talking about finding both volumes for him to take. I originally thought they had made it up, it sounds so silly, but then the first page appeared on a sample AP test, but I never thought much about it. <br/><br/>And now here we are, in our chronological read of all the Dickens novels, engaging with the story of Mr Paul Dombey, his lon</span>
  <span id="freeText13085198082561420740" style="display:none">This was a huge saga, and I'm kind of shocked that it isn't more widely regarded/read. I first heard about it from Little Women, when Jo is packing up Laurie for school and talking about finding both volumes for him to take. I originally thought they had made it up, it sounds so silly, but then the first page appeared on a sample AP test, but I never thought much about it. <br /><br />And now here we are, in our chronological read of all the Dickens novels, engaging with the story of Mr Paul Dombey, his long-awaited son (Paul Dombey) and what befalls their family and their connections. Pride, greed, honesty, virtue, the ups and downs of this family consume the story and the reader. My sister pointed out that Dombey sr. is a precursor for Scrooge, and I agree, but I think maybe he deserved to be haunted a bit longer. <br /><br />And I just adored Captain Cuttles, and was quite surprised by Edith, and I hope that Rob the Grinder makes good at last. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13085198082561420740" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


